#!/bin/bash 

jwtd() {
    if [[ -x $(command -v jq) ]]; then
         jq -R 'split(".") | .[0],.[1] | @base64d | fromjson' <<< "${1}"
         echo "Signature: $(echo "${1}" | awk -F'.' '{print $3}')"
    fi
}

-----------------------
This is a simple and efficient Bash function that decodes a JSON Web Token (JWT) 
to display its header and payload in a human-readable format, and separately 
outputs the signature.

Description

The jwtd function takes a single argument—a JWT string—and breaks it down into 
its three constituent parts: Header, Payload, and Signature. It

How to Use

1. Add the function to your shell configuration file: ~/.bashrc, ~/.zshrc, or ~/.bash_profile
2. Reload your shell configuration (e.g., source ~/.bashrc) or open a new terminal.
3. Run the function with a JWT as the argument: jwtd <your_jwt_string>
